{"meta":{"spec_version":"0.3","created":"2025-01-01T00:00:00Z","author":"OpenChronology Demo"},"event":{"id":"hundred-years-war","type":"era","content":{"title":"Hundred Years' War","date_label":"1337 – 1453","description":"The **Hundred Years' War** was a series of conflicts between the kingdoms of England and France lasting 116 years, driven primarily by English claims to the French throne.\n\nThe war produced some of the most iconic figures of medieval history: **Edward, the Black Prince**, the archer-victory at Agincourt (1415) under Henry V, and most memorably **Joan of Arc** — the young peasant woman whose visions led her to command French forces and reverse the tide of the war before her execution in 1431.\n\nThe conflict ended English ambitions on the continent and accelerated the development of French national identity. The longbow-armed English armies revolutionized medieval warfare, undermining the dominance of armored knights and presaging the age of gunpowder.","description_format":"markdown","tags":["hundred-years-war","france","england","joan-of-arc","agincourt","medieval"],"sources":[{"title":"Hundred Years' War — Encyclopedia Britannica","url":"https://www.britannica.com/event/Hundred-Years-War"}]},"temporal":{"calendar":"gregorian","start_value":"1337","end_value":"1453","precision":"year"},"significance":{"value":840,"temporal_scope":"decades","geographic_scope":"western-europe"}}}
